ce:section.ce:para:
For the synthesis of GQDs, bovine serum albumin powder (500 mg) was stirred with 50 mL of DI water. The solution was poured into a hydrothermal processor insulated with Teflon and fired in a vacuum oven at 180 °C for 12 h. Afterward the process, the autoclave was left to cool to normal temperature gradually. The solution changed to a pale-yellow solution during the hydrothermal process, revealing the formation of bovine serum albumin-derived GQDs (
                           Scheme 1

                           ). The GQDs were then purified using a dialysis membrane after being filtered to remove larger nanoparticles with a 0.2 µm filter. After dialysis, the dialyzed solution was dried using lyophilized to yield a fine powder of pure bovine serum albumin-derived GQDs for forthcoming usage. Besides, the pH-dependent stability of greenly produced GQDs was studied at different pH such as 3, 5, 7, 8, 9, 11, 13, etc. In brief, the pH of the bovine serum albumin-derived GQDs solution was altered to 3, 5, 7, 8, 9, 11, and 13 using a 1 M solution of NaOH and 1 M HCl at ambient temperature. Afterward, the pH of the solution was then evidenced with a digital pH meter before being placed aside for at least 60 min. To determine the cause of the pH, photoluminescence, and zeta potential were monitored which can assist the protonation and deprotonation of functional groups on the exterior of GQDs [45]. For the functionalization of GQDs, 10 mg of PLGA was added to 100 mL of bovine serum albumin-derived GQDs (100 µg/mL). After this, a magnetic stirrer has been utilized to heat the blend for approximately 2 h around 50 °C at 200 rpm. To achieve 30 °C, the mixture was left undisturbed for some time. To end, the pale-yellow GQDs were centrifuged for 10 min at 30,000 rpm before being dissolved in 10 mL DI water for highly blue luminescent PLGA-fGQDs.
